1
00:04:18,468 --> 00:04:19,507
All right.

2
00:04:19,507 --> 00:04:21,786
I know, I know, I know.

3
00:04:21,788 --> 00:04:25,425
A gun...
It's dangerous for no one except you.

4
00:04:25,427 --> 00:04:28,105
You know what I want, don't you?

5
00:04:28,105 --> 00:04:30,100
Yes.

6
00:04:30,185 --> 00:04:33,144
You're wasting time.
Don't fuck with me!

7
00:04:33,146 --> 00:04:36,220
Open it. Open it!

8
00:04:49,981 --> 00:04:52,009
Open it!

9
00:04:58,620 --> 00:05:00,093
Give me what I want.

10
00:05:00,093 --> 00:05:01,939
I don't understand,
I don't have anything else.

11
00:05:01,939 --> 00:05:05,300
If the man's offering you
all that money, I'd take it.

12
00:05:05,420 --> 00:05:08,577
When I need financial advice,
I'll call my broker.

13
00:05:08,579 --> 00:05:10,577
- I'm just saying, is all.
- Whatever.

14
00:05:10,579 --> 00:05:14,016
Take off your coat.
Take off your coat!

15
00:05:24,096 --> 00:05:26,855
- Now, how hard was that?
- Excuse me.

16
00:05:26,855 --> 00:05:29,930
Mister, I thought I told...

17
00:05:33,175 --> 00:05:34,963
What the?...

18
00:05:39,374 --> 00:05:42,322
Go, go! Move! Everybody down!

19
00:05:43,733 --> 00:05:45,211
Move! Move!

20
00:05:45,213 --> 00:05:48,242
Move!

21
00:05:59,689 --> 00:06:01,559
Go, go, go!

22
00:06:01,649 --> 00:06:04,807
Suspect white or Hispanic male.
Wearing a reflective vest.

23
00:06:04,809 --> 00:06:07,918
He's on top of the cars.
All units at Vernon Jackson.

24
00:06:14,526 --> 00:06:17,283
Everybody down! Stay down!

25
00:06:18,646 --> 00:06:20,560
Other end!

26
00:06:33,004 --> 00:06:37,079
Everybody down!
Keep moving! Keep moving!

27
00:07:14,877 --> 00:07:18,435
Move, move! Everybody down!
Face down on the platform!

28
00:07:18,435 --> 00:07:20,713
Come on, face down!
Everybody off the train!

29
00:07:20,714 --> 00:07:23,514
Come on, face down!
Get down!

30
00:07:25,927 --> 00:07:27,913
- Officer...
- Move!

31
00:07:27,913 --> 00:07:29,872
Come on, guys, get down!

32
00:07:29,874 --> 00:07:32,231
Get your ass down!
Get down!

33
00:07:32,233 --> 00:07:35,151
Get down! Search the tracks!

34
00:07:35,153 --> 00:07:39,262
He went down the tunnel?
Check the tunnel, check the roof.

35
00:07:44,911 --> 00:07:47,269
Come on, people!
Face down on the ground now!

36
00:07:47,271 --> 00:07:50,069
He jumped!
He was on the roof!

37
00:07:50,069 --> 00:07:53,468
This train is closed.
Nobody gets on.

38
00:07:53,470 --> 00:07:55,627
Sir, I need you to calm down.

39
00:07:55,629 --> 00:07:58,340
Get these people moving.

40
00:08:06,706 --> 00:08:09,338
Stop right there.

41
00:08:11,065 --> 00:08:13,264
The punk's got balls...

42
00:08:13,266 --> 00:08:15,464
but no positive identification.

43
00:08:15,466 --> 00:08:19,177
No... huh, there's another
camera pointing at the platform.

44
00:08:24,223 --> 00:08:26,423
Michaels, stop it right there.

45
00:08:27,663 --> 00:08:29,062
You see what I see?

46
00:08:29,062 --> 00:08:31,542
- Maybe.
- That's him, Lieutenant.

47
00:08:31,543 --> 00:08:32,621
That's who?

48
00:08:32,623 --> 00:08:34,040
How long have you been
a detective, Micheals?

49
00:08:34,042 --> 00:08:35,540
11 months, sir.

50
00:08:35,542 --> 00:08:37,341
I'm 22 years in robbery
and homicide.

51
00:08:37,341 --> 00:08:40,500
One of your subcategories
of robbery is art theft.

52
00:08:40,500 --> 00:08:43,779
There's a lot of that in the Apple.
Are you aware of that, Michaels?

53
00:08:43,780 --> 00:08:45,379
- I guess so, yeah.
- I wasn't.

54
00:08:45,379 --> 00:08:48,058
When I was your age, I was happy
with regular murder and mayhem.

55
00:08:48,059 --> 00:08:50,658
Lieutenant Weber minored
in art history at Fordham.

56
00:08:50,658 --> 00:08:51,697
Oh.

57
00:08:51,698 --> 00:08:54,498
Anyway, the Chief starts
calling me Lieutenant Picasso...

58
00:08:54,499 --> 00:08:57,177
and puts me in charge
every time there is the theft...

59
00:08:57,177 --> 00:08:58,657
of as much as an Etch-A-Sketch.

60
00:08:58,658 --> 00:09:02,535
Two decades,
I've been putting 'em all away.

61
00:09:02,537 --> 00:09:05,216
Everybody but him, Keith Ripley.

62
00:09:05,216 --> 00:09:09,167
He's the best there is.
Howdy, Keith.

63
00:09:36,091 --> 00:09:38,085
You've been bad boy.

64
00:09:40,090 --> 00:09:43,328
- Perhaps I could give you 15.
- No.

65
00:09:43,330 --> 00:09:44,969
That is not possible.

66
00:09:44,970 --> 00:09:46,648
I wouldn't take less than 100.

67
00:09:48,928 --> 00:09:51,326
I'm just saying, is all.

68
00:09:51,327 --> 00:09:54,357
- You...
- Mind if I borrow this?

69
00:09:54,528 --> 00:09:57,885
- Well, I may have wanted to use it.
- Mm.

70
00:09:57,886 --> 00:10:00,200
But yours will do.

71
00:10:00,647 --> 00:10:02,005
Will you please put down my gun?

72
00:10:02,006 --> 00:10:04,884
There's one thing
you should be aware of, Gabriel,

73
00:10:04,885 --> 00:10:07,245
or do you prefer Seńor Martin?

74
00:10:07,245 --> 00:10:09,884
The police cannot arrest you
for armed robbery,

75
00:10:09,884 --> 00:10:11,323
if your gun isn't loaded.

76
00:10:11,325 --> 00:10:12,524
Your point?

77
00:10:12,524 --> 00:10:15,163
You think I'd walk around
with a loaded shotgun?

78
00:10:15,163 --> 00:10:17,794
Let's see.

79
00:10:19,243 --> 00:10:20,802
- You could have checked.
- Why?

80
00:10:20,802 --> 00:10:24,201
You have my diamonds,
my score, my money.

81
00:10:24,202 --> 00:10:27,596
Enjoy.
Nice meeting you both. Bye.

82
00:10:27,601 --> 00:10:31,995
By the way,
I was going to ask for 125.

83
00:10:32,280 --> 00:10:35,000
I'm just saying, is all.

84
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:37,038
- Gabriel, stay.
- Why?

85
00:10:37,039 --> 00:10:40,513
What else do you want?
You gonna shoot me now?

86
00:10:41,039 --> 00:10:43,197
Well, in as much as
you did steal the diamonds,

87
00:10:43,198 --> 00:10:46,597
I figure it's only fair
to share the proceeds with you.

88
00:10:46,599 --> 00:10:49,912
So to what do I owe
this act of generosity?

89
00:10:50,638 --> 00:10:54,394
I have a proposition
I wish to discuss with you.

90
00:10:57,557 --> 00:10:59,034
So...

91
00:10:59,036 --> 00:11:01,115
how did you know
I would come here,

92
00:11:01,115 --> 00:11:02,514
as well as my name?

93
00:11:02,515 --> 00:11:04,153
It's part of the proposition...

94
00:11:06,315 --> 00:11:08,832
Oh, shit!

95
00:11:09,235 --> 00:11:12,866
- Come on:
- All right, take it easy, take it easy.

96
00:11:13,673 --> 00:11:16,065
Nicky would like his money.

97
00:11:16,913 --> 00:11:19,543
- Ask him.
- Thank you.

98
00:11:19,913 --> 00:11:23,711
This is between you and them.
Got nothing to do with me.

99
00:11:23,711 --> 00:11:26,547
Everything does now.

100
00:11:28,030 --> 00:11:31,070
Call this interest.
Nicky is tired of waiting for you.

101
00:11:41,509 --> 00:11:43,787
You must have very bad karma.

102
00:11:43,788 --> 00:11:46,667
I actually don't believe in it.
Still, about this propos...

103
00:11:46,668 --> 00:11:50,426
No, no, no, no!
You're totally out of your mind.

104
00:11:50,427 --> 00:11:52,784
Good night.

105
00:11:56,306 --> 00:11:57,745
- Hey.
- What?

106
00:11:57,745 --> 00:12:00,422
Here's your karma.

107
00:12:02,225 --> 00:12:07,062
- What was in the other envelope?
- Your cut.

108
00:12:09,224 --> 00:12:11,297
Now you've got mine.

109
00:12:12,543 --> 00:12:13,822
Whatever.

110
00:12:13,822 --> 00:12:17,216
- Think about it.
- Yeah, sure, yeah.

111
00:12:41,857 --> 00:12:44,250
Hmm.

112
00:12:47,017 --> 00:12:50,125
Now... what do you want?

113
00:12:51,056 --> 00:12:53,288
A partner.

114
00:12:53,696 --> 00:12:56,405
What'd you think
I was doing on that train?

115
00:12:56,455 --> 00:12:59,134
- I was watching you work.
- Hm.

116
00:12:59,134 --> 00:13:02,493
I've been your shadow
ever since you got to town.

117
00:13:02,494 --> 00:13:06,967
So why were you in my town
robbing subways?

118
00:13:07,173 --> 00:13:10,491
It's hurricane season in Miami.
I don't like hurricanes.

119
00:13:10,493 --> 00:13:14,090
Or you didn't feel like
going back to Angola.

120
00:13:14,812 --> 00:13:16,850
It's over.
Lesson learned.

121
00:13:16,851 --> 00:13:18,210
Look...

122
00:13:18,211 --> 00:13:20,049
Gabriel Martin is a rock star.

123
00:13:20,051 --> 00:13:24,168
So why were you holding
open-mike night on the subway...

124
00:13:24,169 --> 00:13:26,562
for a lousy 100 grand?

125
00:13:27,289 --> 00:13:28,349
Two reasons...

126
00:13:28,350 --> 00:13:30,888
Yes, Miami was getting too hot.

127
00:13:30,889 --> 00:13:33,998
And perhaps you can relate to this.

128
00:13:34,048 --> 00:13:36,076
Sometimes...

129
00:13:37,048 --> 00:13:39,998
Sometimes you just need
to feel the rush.

130
00:13:41,846 --> 00:13:43,765
The juice.

131
00:13:43,767 --> 00:13:45,286
Yeah.

132
00:13:45,287 --> 00:13:47,519
You know what I mean.

133
00:13:47,966 --> 00:13:50,004
Yesterday,
you took down two jewelers...

134
00:13:50,005 --> 00:13:52,796
for a few stones from Romanov's.

135
00:13:53,164 --> 00:13:55,724
My idea is Romanov's itself.

136
00:13:55,725 --> 00:13:58,003
Please...

137
00:13:58,004 --> 00:14:03,081
Specifically, two Fabergé eggs
worth 20 million dollars...

138
00:14:03,562 --> 00:14:05,921
Each.

139
00:14:07,322 --> 00:14:09,840
It's a two-man job.

140
00:14:10,721 --> 00:14:13,513
Do I have your attention?

141
00:14:33,918 --> 00:14:35,866
Wait here.

142
00:14:36,677 --> 00:14:40,707
I hear they prefer cash...
or your first-born.

143
00:15:03,552 --> 00:15:06,547
Why don't you try
The Standard instead?

144
00:15:10,030 --> 00:15:11,990
Jealous?

145
00:15:11,990 --> 00:15:14,019
Of who?

146
00:15:14,750 --> 00:15:16,469
The mystery bandit.

147
00:15:16,470 --> 00:15:19,703
I'm afraid that type of thing
is not my style.

148
00:15:20,149 --> 00:15:24,908
Well, I think this guy's
got panache... guts.

149
00:15:25,629 --> 00:15:28,706
And a passing resemblance,
at least in body type.

150
00:15:30,427 --> 00:15:33,586
Well, you don't have
to rob trains to have panache.

151
00:15:33,586 --> 00:15:38,697
Or guts... but you've gotta admit that
kind of thing immediately brands you.

152
00:15:42,625 --> 00:15:46,183
My treat... too painful watching
you attempt to read Cyrillic.

153
00:15:46,184 --> 00:15:49,182
Oh, no, no, no... I was just... huh,
looking at the picture.

154
00:15:49,183 --> 00:15:51,258
So you are jealous.

155
00:15:52,344 --> 00:15:56,054
Yes... you got me there.
Absolutely.

156
00:15:58,302 --> 00:16:01,100
I've gotta get this...
Chinese food to my boss...

157
00:16:01,101 --> 00:16:03,100
so, um...

158
00:16:03,101 --> 00:16:05,100
some other time.

159
00:16:05,100 --> 00:16:07,899
- When, some other time?
- I'll call you.

160
00:16:07,900 --> 00:16:10,938
But you don't have my number
or know my name or anything.

161
00:16:10,940 --> 00:16:12,339
I guess that could be a problem.

162
00:16:12,340 --> 00:16:14,208
Gabriel.

163
00:16:15,220 --> 00:16:16,738
- Oh, shit!
- Are you with him?

164
00:16:16,739 --> 00:16:18,857
I don't know.
Should I? More or less.

165
00:16:18,859 --> 00:16:21,217
Ahh... yes, I am.

166
00:16:21,219 --> 00:16:23,451
What'd you want?

167
00:16:23,778 --> 00:16:26,096
Can't I bring my goddaughter
a birthday present?

168
00:16:26,097 --> 00:16:27,536
My birthday was last month.

169
00:16:27,537 --> 00:16:30,056
It was two weeks ago
and I'm sorry it's late.

170
00:16:30,057 --> 00:16:34,370
Alex, it's just a present.
No strings.

171
00:16:35,056 --> 00:16:36,845
No thanks.

172
00:16:38,336 --> 00:16:41,171
Well, it was nice
to have almost met you, Gabriel.

173
00:16:41,254 --> 00:16:43,653
- Gaby.
- Gaby.

174
00:16:43,654 --> 00:16:47,014
It's a shame you don't keep
a higher class of company.

175
00:16:52,493 --> 00:16:56,250
- Don't even think about it.
- Think about what?

176
00:16:56,251 --> 00:16:59,250
You go anywhere near her.
I'll rip your heart out. I mean it.

177
00:16:59,251 --> 00:17:03,282
It looks like it's your heart,
she's not so fond of.

178
00:17:03,770 --> 00:17:06,163
You were warned.
Let's go.

179
00:17:06,450 --> 00:17:08,409
I thought you said
the target was Romanov's.

180
00:17:08,410 --> 00:17:11,328
- This is research.
- Research?

181
00:17:11,329 --> 00:17:13,607
Oh, wow!

182
00:17:17,968 --> 00:17:20,759
They're absolutely stunning.

183
00:17:22,607 --> 00:17:24,526
They are.

184
00:17:24,527 --> 00:17:27,326
Between 1885 and 1916...

185
00:17:27,326 --> 00:17:30,525
Fabergé produced 50 of these
Easter eggs for the Empress...

186
00:17:30,526 --> 00:17:33,045
and her daughter-in-law,
the Czarina Alexandra.

187
00:17:33,046 --> 00:17:34,923
Should I take notes?

188
00:17:34,924 --> 00:17:36,804
Will there be a quiz?

189
00:17:36,805 --> 00:17:39,962
No quiz but there will be a test.

190
00:17:39,963 --> 00:17:45,402
Okay... the Fabergés are all made
of precious metals and fine jewels.

191
00:17:45,403 --> 00:17:49,082
- Every one a unique masterpiece.
- Indeed.

192
00:17:49,083 --> 00:17:51,361
Most are on display in the Kremlin.

193
00:17:51,362 --> 00:17:55,080
The rest in private collections,
museums... or lost.

194
00:17:55,082 --> 00:17:58,269
In this case, at Romanov's.

195
00:17:58,441 --> 00:18:00,519
Who is your buyer?

196
00:18:00,520 --> 00:18:02,159
You don't want to know.

197
00:18:02,160 --> 00:18:05,358
Oh, I'm stealing 40 million dollars
worth of eggs so I want to know.

198
00:18:05,359 --> 00:18:07,837
I also want to know
why these particular eggs...

199
00:18:07,838 --> 00:18:10,230
are even worth 40 million dollars.

200
00:18:10,798 --> 00:18:14,031
Because no one knows they exist.

201
00:18:14,038 --> 00:18:15,396
Oh.

202
00:18:15,397 --> 00:18:18,356
- The so-called mystery eggs?
- Mm-hm.

203
00:18:18,357 --> 00:18:22,316
Yeah, I've heard rumors,
but I thought it was just a myth.

204
00:18:22,317 --> 00:18:26,835
Last year, they turned up...
at Romanov's.

205
00:18:26,836 --> 00:18:28,634
So how do you know this?

206
00:18:28,635 --> 00:18:33,273
I was partners with a man named
Victor Korolenko... Alex's father.

207
00:18:33,275 --> 00:18:35,074
He was in tight with the Russians.

208
00:18:35,075 --> 00:18:37,792
What they knew, he knew.

209
00:18:37,794 --> 00:18:40,472
So, why aren't you
pulling this job with him?

210
00:18:40,473 --> 00:18:43,192
Let's just say
he's no longer around.

211
00:18:43,192 --> 00:18:46,143
Leave it at that.

212
00:18:49,352 --> 00:18:50,911
He's gone.

213
00:18:50,912 --> 00:18:53,190
You're here.

214
00:18:53,990 --> 00:18:56,383
Now we just have to deliver.

215
00:18:58,230 --> 00:19:00,628
- Ripley...
- Hmm?

216
00:19:00,630 --> 00:19:02,419
Why?

217
00:19:03,109 --> 00:19:05,387
Why risk your freedom at all?

218
00:19:05,669 --> 00:19:07,708
This will not be
anything close to easy.

219
00:19:07,709 --> 00:19:09,666
You are not in jail in the present.

220
00:19:09,667 --> 00:19:13,778
- Are you not comfortable?
- I'm never comfortable.

221
00:19:14,107 --> 00:19:17,579
Some people
were born to compose music.

222
00:19:18,106 --> 00:19:20,657
Others to split the atom.

223
00:19:22,665 --> 00:19:25,695
I was born to steal shit.

224
00:19:27,184 --> 00:19:29,623
Hold out your hand.

225
00:19:30,305 --> 00:19:32,173
Hand?

226
00:19:36,384 --> 00:19:40,142
That coin was given to me by Victor
when we became partners.

227
00:19:40,143 --> 00:19:42,621
The coin represents
a Russian phrase.

228
00:19:42,622 --> 00:19:48,540
"Vorovoslky mir".
Loosely translated, thieves' world.

229
00:19:48,780 --> 00:19:50,180
Victor belonged to it.

230
00:19:50,181 --> 00:19:52,209
Now...

231
00:19:52,421 --> 00:19:55,096
you belong to it.

232
00:20:31,413 --> 00:20:33,652
Psst... Hey!

233
00:20:33,653 --> 00:20:37,291
You misunderstand.
Ripley's just... huh, business.

234
00:20:37,292 --> 00:20:39,131
This is... huh...

235
00:20:39,132 --> 00:20:41,330
Stalking?

236
00:20:41,971 --> 00:20:46,080
Well... if you had given me
your number, I would have called first.

237
00:20:46,611 --> 00:20:49,528
Those are two
very flawed assumptions.

238
00:20:49,529 --> 00:20:51,128
Do you have a vase?

239
00:20:51,130 --> 00:20:53,048
I just took these
from a roadside shrine...

240
00:20:53,049 --> 00:20:56,268
and I think they need some, huh...
water.

241
00:20:56,269 --> 00:20:57,728
Huh...

242
00:20:57,729 --> 00:21:02,362
- May I use that... huh, thing over there?
- Sure...

243
00:21:02,567 --> 00:21:08,066
I... I've noticed this... huh,
Russian nightclub, down the block, huh...

244
00:21:08,067 --> 00:21:10,086
Riga Rose
or something like that.

245
00:21:10,086 --> 00:21:12,922
Why don't we meet there
after work?

246
00:21:17,644 --> 00:21:19,673
I'm busy.

247
00:21:19,845 --> 00:21:23,083
- I'll wait.
- I won't show.

248
00:21:23,084 --> 00:21:25,681
I'll take my chances.

249
00:21:28,243 --> 00:21:31,882
Do svidanja, Alexandra.

250
00:21:31,883 --> 00:21:36,161
Research. Keith Ripley.
'93, the Brooklyn Museum.

251
00:21:36,162 --> 00:21:39,000
'94, the Diamond District Warehouse
and then in '95...

252
00:21:39,001 --> 00:21:42,319
I'm very familiar
with Ripley's life story, Michaels.

253
00:21:42,320 --> 00:21:45,598
In fact, I busted him twice.

254
00:21:45,599 --> 00:21:48,078
Both times he walked
because of good lawyering.

255
00:21:48,079 --> 00:21:50,958
Exactly, so I thought
why not swing for the fences?

256
00:21:50,959 --> 00:21:52,837
Murder one, Victor Korolenko.

257
00:21:52,838 --> 00:21:55,677
Thinkin ' of the Brighton Beach steam bath?
Forget it. There was no...

258
00:21:55,679 --> 00:21:58,557
- No body. But we've got a ton of forensics.
- And no witnesses.

259
00:21:58,557 --> 00:22:01,517
Nobody there admitted
to seeing a thing.

260
00:22:01,518 --> 00:22:04,915
I was this close to convincing
Korolenko to take witness protection,

261
00:22:04,916 --> 00:22:07,155
in exchange for giving up Ripley.

262
00:22:07,156 --> 00:22:09,674
But Ripley got to him first.

263
00:22:09,675 --> 00:22:11,275
I can't prove it.

264
00:22:11,276 --> 00:22:13,473
Right, okay. I see, I see... okay.

265
00:22:13,474 --> 00:22:16,394
No...
what you don't see, Michaels,

266
00:22:16,394 --> 00:22:19,272
is why Ripley got involved
in a small-time caper,

267
00:22:19,273 --> 00:22:22,432
like grabbin ' a few diamonds
off of some couriers on a subway.

268
00:22:22,433 --> 00:22:23,512
And neither did I.

269
00:22:23,513 --> 00:22:26,587
Until I read
the Dutch guy's statement.

270
00:22:27,792 --> 00:22:30,502
Those diamonds
came from Romanov's.

271
00:22:31,112 --> 00:22:35,426
You mean Ripley and his new partner
are planning to take down Romanov's?

272
00:22:35,590 --> 00:22:38,289
Ah... come on.
Like that could ever happen.

273
00:22:38,290 --> 00:22:41,988
Not even Ripley
could take down a place like that.

274
00:22:42,390 --> 00:22:44,179
Wanna bet?

275
00:23:10,025 --> 00:23:12,104
- Hi.
- Hi.

276
00:23:12,105 --> 00:23:15,502
- You know this place very well.
- I never said I didn't.

277
00:23:15,503 --> 00:23:17,702
Let's face it,
you didn't see the nightclub.

278
00:23:17,703 --> 00:23:21,342
You saw the flyer in the fax
and then you made an assumption.

279
00:23:21,343 --> 00:23:24,461
Yeah. Guilty. So I did.

280
00:23:24,462 --> 00:23:28,381
Never assume anything,
especially down here.

281
00:23:28,382 --> 00:23:30,901
- How mysterious.
- What?

282
00:23:30,902 --> 00:23:33,539
How mysterious.

283
00:23:33,540 --> 00:23:35,779
- Can I buy you a drink?
- I don't drink.

284
00:23:35,780 --> 00:23:38,695
Another assumption.

285
00:23:39,900 --> 00:23:42,417
You wanna dance?

286
00:23:44,778 --> 00:23:46,538
Yeah.

287
00:23:46,538 --> 00:23:50,647
I'm willing to make a fool of myself.
Why not?

288
00:24:44,288 --> 00:24:46,964
Here.

289
00:24:47,927 --> 00:24:49,566
- And for him.
- Thank you.

290
00:24:49,567 --> 00:24:50,806
Thanks.

291
00:24:50,807 --> 00:24:52,486
I thought all Russians drank.

292
00:24:52,487 --> 00:24:55,684
Translation,
we're a race of suicidal alcoholics.

293
00:24:55,685 --> 00:24:58,045
No... I didn't mean that. No.

294
00:24:58,046 --> 00:25:01,200
Actually, we are.
Cheers.

295
00:25:01,285 --> 00:25:03,564
- Nastravila?
- Nastravise

296
00:25:03,565 --> 00:25:05,284
Nastravise?
Mm'mm

297
00:25:06,403 --> 00:25:11,083
So... how is it...
working for the lawyer?

298
00:25:11,284 --> 00:25:14,902
- Huh... I'm a lawyer, too, you know.
- Oh.

299
00:25:14,903 --> 00:25:18,601
Maybe I won't say another word,
because everything I say is wrong.

300
00:25:18,602 --> 00:25:21,560
- Well, you don't know until you try.
- True.

301
00:25:21,561 --> 00:25:24,559
Besides, my father warned me
about being a lawyer.

302
00:25:24,560 --> 00:25:27,680
He told me I should try and do
something honest with my life.

303
00:25:27,681 --> 00:25:29,999
As if he would know.

304
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:34,711
Your father and Ripley,
they were close, right?

305
00:25:36,838 --> 00:25:39,277
Once upon a time.

306
00:25:41,478 --> 00:25:44,666
I'm sure Ripley told you.
My father's dead.

307
00:25:45,277 --> 00:25:48,836
Now Ripley likes
to try to take care of me.

308
00:25:48,836 --> 00:25:51,830
Pay for stuff. That kind of thing.

309
00:25:52,036 --> 00:25:55,474
Of course, it's the least he can do.

310
00:25:55,476 --> 00:25:59,153
Sorry. I don't mean to pry.

311
00:26:03,953 --> 00:26:05,553
Yes, you do.

312
00:26:08,393 --> 00:26:11,229
Now who is making assumptions?

313
00:26:11,752 --> 00:26:16,227
No, Gaby. I'm not assuming a thing.

314
00:26:31,269 --> 00:26:33,626
You wanna know about Ripley?

315
00:26:35,427 --> 00:26:37,580
Stay away.

316
00:27:14,901 --> 00:27:17,419
You son of a bitch!

317
00:27:18,980 --> 00:27:20,858
Well... you dropped these...

318
00:27:20,859 --> 00:27:24,898
and I am a gentleman
bringing them back to you.

319
00:27:24,900 --> 00:27:27,529
Uh-huh.

320
00:27:31,019 --> 00:27:33,410
No, no, no, no, no!

321
00:27:34,938 --> 00:27:37,010
No!

322
00:28:24,689 --> 00:28:27,843
Shit, man! What do you want?

323
00:28:28,407 --> 00:28:31,085
I told you to leave her alone.

324
00:28:31,488 --> 00:28:34,086
I'm not gonna tell you again.

325
00:28:34,086 --> 00:28:37,878
Get dressed. I'll be downstairs.

326
00:28:44,644 --> 00:28:46,877
Son of a bitch.

327
00:28:50,683 --> 00:28:52,711
Fascinating.

328
00:28:53,844 --> 00:28:57,395
You could start a whole new trend
in interior design.

329
00:28:59,802 --> 00:29:02,320
- What are these?
- What do they look like?

330
00:29:02,321 --> 00:29:04,361
Police IDs?

331
00:29:04,362 --> 00:29:08,631
There's a reception at Romanov's
tonight, honoring the NYPD.

332
00:29:09,161 --> 00:29:11,919
And our invitation's just arrived.

333
00:29:11,920 --> 00:29:13,239
A cop for the night.

334
00:29:13,240 --> 00:29:15,838
And all the doughnuts you can eat.

335
00:29:15,839 --> 00:29:18,758
Meanwhile, however,
I need you to go to the dry-cleaners.

336
00:29:18,759 --> 00:29:22,238
Why don't you go and pick up
your dry-cleaning yourself, sir?

337
00:29:22,239 --> 00:29:24,914
Who said anything about picking up?

338
00:29:25,837 --> 00:29:27,912
You're dropping off.

339
00:30:04,990 --> 00:30:07,509
Cellphone, please.

340
00:30:36,144 --> 00:30:38,104
- Commissioner Rawls.
- Gentlemen.

341
00:30:38,105 --> 00:30:40,064
Deputy Commissioner Morelli.

342
00:30:40,065 --> 00:30:41,942
Such a pleasure having you here.

343
00:30:41,943 --> 00:30:44,462
May we give you gentlemen
the grand tour?

344
00:30:44,463 --> 00:30:46,662
- The secrets of Romanov?
- You might say so.

345
00:30:46,663 --> 00:30:49,294
- Thank you. We're honored.
- Please.

346
00:30:54,021 --> 00:30:56,661
The guards,
all FSB secret police.

347
00:30:56,662 --> 00:30:59,940
Every door, every inch of glass
wired and alarmed.

348
00:30:59,941 --> 00:31:04,528
So even if a bird flies in here,
you know about it.

349
00:31:04,619 --> 00:31:06,219
Topkapi.

350
00:31:06,220 --> 00:31:07,659
Rififi.

351
00:31:07,660 --> 00:31:11,498
No, the bird flew into the museum,
landed on the wire...

352
00:31:11,499 --> 00:31:13,897
and set off the alarm in Topkapi.

353
00:31:13,898 --> 00:31:15,376
You're a cineaste.

354
00:31:15,377 --> 00:31:18,645
Actually, I only see heist movies.

355
00:31:19,577 --> 00:31:22,855
Well, the lesson to take away from
the bird flying into the museum...

356
00:31:22,856 --> 00:31:27,414
is no matter how well you planned,
always be ready to improvise...

357
00:31:27,415 --> 00:31:30,414
because, I guarantee you,
something's gonna go wrong.

358
00:31:30,415 --> 00:31:33,094
- I'd prefer to avoid that.
- Uh-huh.

359
00:31:33,095 --> 00:31:36,573
How comprehensive
is the surveillance system?

360
00:31:36,574 --> 00:31:38,692
Let's take a look.

361
00:31:58,411 --> 00:32:00,888
- Smart card for the elevator.
- And all the doors.

362
00:32:00,890 --> 00:32:03,009
This way. After you.

363
00:32:03,009 --> 00:32:04,798
We're on.

364
00:32:06,929 --> 00:32:10,163
Good to see you, old friend.
Let me introduce you.

365
00:32:10,688 --> 00:32:14,719
Lieutenant Weber, I presume.

366
00:32:14,807 --> 00:32:18,365
You know, Ripley,
identity theft is a serious crime.

367
00:32:18,366 --> 00:32:21,204
- And quite an embarrassing one in this case.
- Really?

368
00:32:21,205 --> 00:32:22,964
Do you realize
how ashamed I felt...

369
00:32:22,965 --> 00:32:26,444
telling that nice lady at the door
that I was still a lieutenant?

370
00:32:26,445 --> 00:32:28,403
I mean at my age?

371
00:32:28,404 --> 00:32:30,084
Or should I say at your age?

372
00:32:30,085 --> 00:32:33,242
I'm not amused.
What are you doing here?

373
00:32:33,243 --> 00:32:36,603
And why did you appropriate
my invitation? As if I didn't know.

374
00:32:36,604 --> 00:32:38,721
I apologize for the subterfuge.

375
00:32:38,722 --> 00:32:42,481
I just wanted to show my friend here
some of the finer things in life.

376
00:32:42,482 --> 00:32:46,441
If you want to arrest us for impersonating
police officers, go right ahead.

377
00:32:46,442 --> 00:32:48,800
I'm sure my lawyer
will have us out in two hours.

378
00:32:48,801 --> 00:32:52,000
It'd be a delightful two hours.
Get your hands down.

379
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:55,479
Then there's all that explaining
you'd have to do to your superiors.

380
00:32:55,480 --> 00:32:57,439
Now that would be
an embarrassment.

381
00:32:57,440 --> 00:33:02,198
Notorious thief gaining admittance
pretending to be you.

382
00:33:02,199 --> 00:33:03,557
Great police work, Weber.

383
00:33:03,558 --> 00:33:06,277
We should discuss my police work
when this is all over.

384
00:33:06,278 --> 00:33:07,676
Hmm.

385
00:33:07,678 --> 00:33:11,156
- Who's your sidekick?
- Jules Dassin.

386
00:33:11,157 --> 00:33:15,556
Good to meet you, Jules.
I love your movies.

387
00:33:15,557 --> 00:33:17,515
Enjoy the party, gents.

388
00:33:17,516 --> 00:33:20,307
While it lasts.

389
00:33:21,675 --> 00:33:26,034
Now... do you mind telling me
what that was all about?

390
00:33:26,035 --> 00:33:30,190
- Just a cop.
- Really? No kidding.

391
00:33:30,953 --> 00:33:34,592
We have been made in the very place
we are supposed to take down.

392
00:33:34,593 --> 00:33:36,991
Exactly how do you stay out of jail?

393
00:33:36,992 --> 00:33:42,786
Unless, of course, you and this Weber
are partners trying to set me up.

394
00:33:43,392 --> 00:33:45,782
Are you, Ripley?

395
00:33:47,790 --> 00:33:49,029
Here we go.

396
00:33:49,030 --> 00:33:51,468
Come on. Move your damn ass!

397
00:33:54,950 --> 00:33:57,307
Weber has no idea
what we're here for.

398
00:33:57,308 --> 00:33:58,788
Of course he does.

399
00:33:58,788 --> 00:34:00,907
He doesn't know when
and he doesn't know how.

400
00:34:00,909 --> 00:34:02,747
And, no, he doesn't know
about the eggs.

401
00:34:02,748 --> 00:34:04,386
No one does. Here.

402
00:34:04,387 --> 00:34:05,946
The best way to neutralize Weber...

403
00:34:05,948 --> 00:34:09,106
is to fuel his obsession
with busting me.

404
00:34:09,106 --> 00:34:12,864
He's so blinded by it, he no longer
thinks like a cop. Trust me.

405
00:34:12,865 --> 00:34:15,144
Give me a good reason to, huh?

406
00:34:15,146 --> 00:34:18,822
I already gave you 40 million
good reasons. Here.

407
00:34:19,385 --> 00:34:22,623
Now you've seen what the public sees,
it's time for the real treat.

408
00:34:22,625 --> 00:34:26,382
That is, of course, as long as you
promise not to come back and rob us.

409
00:34:26,384 --> 00:34:28,342
I guess I won't take any notes, then.

410
00:34:31,702 --> 00:34:33,581
Our main vault.

411
00:34:33,583 --> 00:34:35,701
Gregor disarm
the motion detectors...

412
00:34:35,702 --> 00:34:38,141
Even with the knowledge
of all protocols,

413
00:34:38,141 --> 00:34:40,579
it is absolutely impregnable.

414
00:34:40,581 --> 00:34:43,619
The voice sensors ask
our head of security, Boris Sergev,

415
00:34:43,621 --> 00:34:45,699
a random set of pre-recorded words.

416
00:34:45,701 --> 00:34:48,659
But this is only half the process.

417
00:34:48,659 --> 00:34:52,777
We also have
a biometric handprint sensor.

418
00:34:52,778 --> 00:34:56,137
Since Mr. Sergev and I are
the only ones who have clearance,

419
00:34:56,139 --> 00:34:58,416
we must both be present
to open the vaults.

420
00:34:58,418 --> 00:35:01,456
Once I activate
the biometric handprint sensor,

421
00:35:01,458 --> 00:35:03,775
he must activate the voice sensor.

422
00:35:03,777 --> 00:35:06,615
This way neither of us
can steal from the other.

423
00:35:06,617 --> 00:35:09,175
Well, you better hope Mr. Sergev
stays healthy.

424
00:35:11,215 --> 00:35:13,215
I must stay
healthy as well!

425
00:35:21,213 --> 00:35:25,561
- Hamburger.
- Hamburger.

426
00:35:26,373 --> 00:35:29,527
- Big Apple.
- Big Apple.

427
00:35:35,572 --> 00:35:37,369
Jesus Christ.

428
00:35:37,371 --> 00:35:40,809
The vault door
automatically resets on the hour...

429
00:35:40,811 --> 00:35:43,889
at which point the sensor
must be activated in reverse...

430
00:35:43,889 --> 00:35:47,648
All In all gentlemen
best not to get locked inside

431
00:35:48,128 --> 00:35:50,047
Well, did I say it was gonna be easy?

432
00:35:50,048 --> 00:35:53,686
No, but you didn't say
it would be impossible either.

433
00:35:53,688 --> 00:35:55,327
Armored glass...

434
00:35:55,327 --> 00:35:59,039
It would take half an hour
to break through just one case.

435
00:35:59,887 --> 00:36:03,286
But, I'm afraid, whoever tried
wouldn't even have half a second...

436
00:36:03,286 --> 00:36:06,724
because an ultrasonic motion detector
would automatically lock him in...

437
00:36:06,726 --> 00:36:08,605
and trigger the alarm.

438
00:36:08,606 --> 00:36:12,083
Containment security gentlemen
Getting in is highly improbable...

439
00:36:12,085 --> 00:36:14,403
But getting out
is frankly impossible.

440
00:36:14,405 --> 00:36:16,202
Where does that door lead to?

441
00:36:16,204 --> 00:36:19,563
To our inner vault which
contains our most precious items...

442
00:36:19,563 --> 00:36:21,561
I'm sorry but security prevents me...

443
00:36:21,563 --> 00:36:24,121
from taking even this
distinguished group in there.

444
00:36:24,123 --> 00:36:26,461
Now we'll proceed back to
the reception, but before we do...

445
00:36:26,463 --> 00:36:28,561
I'd like to, once again,
thank you both...

446
00:36:28,561 --> 00:36:31,681
for your generosity this last year
in helping set up our business.

447
00:36:31,681 --> 00:36:33,960
And thank you very much
for the donation of that chopper.

448
00:36:33,960 --> 00:36:35,320
You're quite welcome.

449
00:36:35,320 --> 00:36:38,599
- Let's go.
- We can do this, Gabriel.

450
00:36:38,599 --> 00:36:41,469
No... Absolutely not.

451
00:36:42,079 --> 00:36:46,030
- It was a pleasure. Goodbye.
- Wait a minute. Wait.

452
00:36:46,679 --> 00:36:48,438
We're not going any where yet.

453
00:36:48,438 --> 00:36:51,117
If Zykov finds that camera,
he's gonna know what it is.

454
00:36:51,117 --> 00:36:53,277
They'll change all the protocols.

455
00:36:53,277 --> 00:36:57,864
Which part of "I don't give a shit"
do you not understand?

456
00:37:15,074 --> 00:37:17,391
Sorry. Let me just...

457
00:37:17,393 --> 00:37:19,391
- I'll handle it.
- No, no, no.

458
00:37:19,393 --> 00:37:22,391
- Please, please. Allow me.
- I'm absolutely okay.

459
00:37:22,391 --> 00:37:24,590
I apologize, sir.

460
00:38:01,664 --> 00:38:03,454
What the fuck?

461
00:38:03,784 --> 00:38:05,023
What the fuck?

462
00:38:05,025 --> 00:38:08,382
Detective Weber, I'm Hal Donley,
special agent in charge of this op.

463
00:38:08,384 --> 00:38:11,222
You're conducting an investigation
of a potential theft...

464
00:38:11,224 --> 00:38:13,702
that you assume is going down
at Romanov Jewelers.

465
00:38:13,702 --> 00:38:15,661
Assume, my ass.

466
00:38:15,663 --> 00:38:18,621
I know it's going down
and I know who's pulling it off.

467
00:38:18,621 --> 00:38:21,260
Except we're asking you
to call off your dogs.

468
00:38:21,262 --> 00:38:23,340
There are other matters
that take precedence.

469
00:38:23,342 --> 00:38:25,099
What could possibly
take precedence...

470
00:38:25,101 --> 00:38:27,739
over the potential theft
of millions of dollars in diamonds...

471
00:38:27,740 --> 00:38:32,532
from a company that donates tons
of money and equipment to the NYPD?

472
00:38:33,579 --> 00:38:35,297
Valentin?

473
00:38:35,298 --> 00:38:37,057
Vitaly Zykov, in the old Soviet days,

474
00:38:37,059 --> 00:38:41,487
was the right-hand man
to a party boss named Dimitri Kuzin.

475
00:38:41,818 --> 00:38:46,655
Kuzin set up a supposedly independent
Russian diamond centre in America.

476
00:38:47,257 --> 00:38:49,045
Romanov's...

477
00:38:49,416 --> 00:38:53,494
But diamonds... they're not all
that he's shipping over here.

478
00:38:53,496 --> 00:38:55,574
He's ripping off
the Russian Treasury, Detective.

479
00:38:55,576 --> 00:38:58,445
Gold, gems, artworks.

480
00:38:58,655 --> 00:39:00,574
Gentlemen, where do you think
Romanov's got the money...

481
00:39:00,574 --> 00:39:04,172
to buy your department a helicopter
and now police cars?

482
00:39:04,173 --> 00:39:05,932
From retail diamond sales?

483
00:39:05,934 --> 00:39:09,769
- So why are they doing this?
- Is that a serious question?

484
00:39:10,652 --> 00:39:13,052
So the NYPD will leave them alone.

485
00:39:13,052 --> 00:39:16,161
That's their mindset.

486
00:39:18,172 --> 00:39:20,489
We need more time
to build our mutual cases.

487
00:39:20,490 --> 00:39:22,969
That's why we can't have
any other investigations...

488
00:39:22,971 --> 00:39:25,840
potentially alerting Zykov.

489
00:39:29,489 --> 00:39:32,007
Lieutenant...

490
00:39:32,489 --> 00:39:34,277
shut it down.

491
00:39:35,929 --> 00:39:39,242
- Gentlemen.
- Commissioner...

492
00:39:40,568 --> 00:39:43,525
Just in case
you think you're smarter than us,

493
00:39:43,527 --> 00:39:46,606
decide to continue this investigation
on a down and low,

494
00:39:46,606 --> 00:39:47,804
forget it.

495
00:39:47,806 --> 00:39:52,315
This is bigger than you and your ego.
Do you get it?

496
00:39:52,925 --> 00:39:55,043
I get it.

497
00:39:57,485 --> 00:40:02,038
- What did the feds have to say?
- Nothing. Everything's still a go.

498
00:40:03,043 --> 00:40:06,762
The first order of business
is to bypass the security cameras.

499
00:40:06,762 --> 00:40:09,561
If we can gain access
into the surveillance system,

500
00:40:09,563 --> 00:40:13,840
we can replace the light feed with
a continuous loop of study shots...

